master.notes: Bringing to television BATMAN, a top selling comic book for almost thirty years, presented something of a challenge to me and Lorenzo Semple, Jr., the principal writer. We were determined to preserve all the wonderful and revered flavour of the comic books and of Bob Kane's immortal characters, yet we also wanted to add an element of "hip" humor to amuse the adult viewers - and we regard almost everyone over fifteen as an adult in this context.Our favorite review is from a southern metropolitan paper whose TV critic watched the opening show with his eleven-year-old son, who, in the midst of the dynamic duo's gyrations, exclaimed, "Daddy stop laughing, this is serious!" Holy Reaction! (William Dozier)------Album first released in 1966. Re-released in 1989 around the buzz created by the new Tim Burton movie adaptation of 'Batman'. Re-released again and remastered in 2014 following the official release of the DVD's of the TV series.

master.notes: This is Thelonious Monk's second album for Columbia Records, planned to be completed over three consecutive afternoons, from February 25 to 27, 1963 at Columbia's 30th Street Studio, N.Y. Session break-down:25 Feb. - Tea For Two (Rouse out)26 Feb. - Think Of One27 Feb. - Tea For Two (Rouse out), Criss Cross, Eronel, Don't Blame Me (piano solo)An additional session necessary to fill up the album on March 29 yielded Pannonica and Crepuscule With Nellie, but Pannonica was not used for this album and only added to the first reissues on CD in 1993. Still too meagre for a full album, two compositions recorded during the first sessions for Columbia in November 1962 were added to finally complete this album, viz. Hackensack and Rhythm-a-ning.
master.title: Criss-Cross

master.notes: Monk's ninth studio album for Columbia, recorded on 14 November: Ellington's "I Didn't Know About You"; a new composition "Green Chimneys" and Fanny Crosby and Phoebe Knapp's "This Is My Story, This Is My Song," and on 15 November 1966: "Locomotive". On 10 January 1967 the quartet recorded the remaining compositions "Straight, No Chaser", "We See" and "Kojo No Tsuki" also known as "Japanese Folk Song," and the session was completed with a solo version of "Between The Devil And The Deep Blue Sea.""This Is My Story, This Is My Song" was not released until 1979 on the compilation [r1591868]. "Green Chimneys" was only released on the CD issue of the album in 1996.Personnel:Charlie Rouse - tenor saxophoneThelonious Monk - pianoLarry Gales - bassBen Riley - drums
